Problem 5.

(a) First, $pi: CC^(n+1) \\ {0} arrow CC PP^n$ is clearly surjective, since every point $[z^1,...,z^(n+1)] in CC PP^n$ has a corresponding element $(z^1,...,z^(n+1)) in CC^(n+1) \\ {0}$, since not all of $z^1,...,z^(n+1)$ are zero, and because $pi((z^1,...,z^(n+1))) = [z^1,...,z^(n+1)]$.

 To show anything else about this map, we must first find the coordinate representation of $CC PP^(n)$. Given $j in [n+1]$, we can look at the open set $U^j$ of points in $CC PP^(n)$ where the $j$th complex coordinate of $[z_1,...,z_(n+1)] in CC PP^(n)$ is non-zero.
 
  Note that $(x+i y)/(z + i w) = (x+i y)(z-i w) dot 1/(z^2+w^2) = 1/(z^2+w^2) (x z + y w + i(y z - x w)) = 1/(z^2+w^2) (x z + y w) +i/(z^2+w^2) (y z- x w)$. Then we can define a chart map $phi^j: U^j arrow RR^(2n)$ by sending $ [x_1 + i x_2,...,x_(2n+1) + i x_(2n+2)] arrow.bar \ 1/(x^2_(2j-1) + x^2_(2j))(x_1 x_(2 j -1) + x_2 x_(2j), x_2 x_(2 j -1) - x_1 x_(2j),...,hat(x)^(2 j -1), hat(x)^(2 j), ...). $ $phi^j$ is smooth, since multiplication, taking/assigning coordinate values of a vector, and addition are smooth. $phi^j$ is also a homeomorphism, where the inverse just gathers pairs of coordinates and multiplies the resulting complex numbers by $1$ (while also adding $1+0i$ to the correct position) to obtain an element equivalent to $phi^j (x)$. Since every element of $CC PP^n$ is contained in one of the $U^j$s and since the composition of two smooth maps is a smooth map, this defines a real smooth structure on $CC PP^n$. Now, let $x in CC^(n+1) \\ {0}$. $x$ has a real representation of $(x^1,x^2,...,x^(2n+2))$, and let's say that $x_(2j - 1) eq.not 0$ or $x_(2 j) eq.not 0$ for some $j in [n+1]$. As in $CC PP^n$, $x$ belongs to an open set $V^j$ which satisfies $y_(2j - 1) eq.not 0$ or $y_(2 j) eq.not 0$ for all $y in V^j$, and the chart map $psi^j$ for this set is determined by the natural map from $CC^(n+1)$ to $RR^(2n+2)$, so $psi^j$ belongs to the smooth structure of this manifold. Also, $pi$ acts on $CC^(n+1)$ by mapping elements to their equivalence classes, and we can do this explicitly on each of the $U^j$s.  Now, $pi(V^j) = U^j$ for obvious reasons, so $phi^j compose pi compose (psi^j)^(-1)$ sends $x=(x^1,...,x^(2n+2))$ to $ 1/(norm(x)) dot norm(x)^2/(x^2_(2j-1) + x^2_(2j)) dot (x_1 x_(2 j -1) + x_2 x_(2j), x_2 x_(2 j -1) - x_1 x_(2j),...,hat(x)^(2 j -1), hat(x)^(2 j), ...) \ = norm(x)/(x^2_(2j-1) + x^2_(2j)) (x_1 x_(2 j -1) + x_2 x_(2j), x_2 x_(2 j -1) - x_1 x_(2j),...,hat(x)^(2 j -1), hat(x)^(2 j), ...). $ This map is smooth, since $x$ is not zero, so $pi$ is smooth. To show that $pi$ is a submersion, observe that some of the smooth local sections of $pi$ on the $V^j$ act by multiplying the representative of an equivalence class by a non-zero complex number. By the definition of a quotient space, each element of $CC^(n+1) \\ {0}$ is in the image of one of these local sections. Hence $pi$ is a smooth submersion by Theorem 4.26.

 (b) We wish to find a surjective smooth submersion $tau: CC^2 \\ {0} arrow SS^2$ such that the fibers of the map $pi: CC^2 \\ {0} arrow CC PP^1$ are constant under $tau$ and vice versa so that Theorem 4.31 can be applied. Consider the map $tau_1: CC^2 \\ {0} arrow SS^3$ given by normalization and the map $tau_2: SS^3 arrow SS^2$ given by $(w,z) arrow.bar (z overline(w) + w overline(z), i w overline(z) - i z overline(w), z overline(z) - w overline(w))$, where $SS^3 := {(w,z): abs(w)^2 + abs(z)^2 = 1} subset.eq CC^2 \\ {0}$. Then we look at the composition map $tau$, which sends $(w,z)$ to $1/(abs(w)^2+abs(z)^2)(z overline(w) + w overline(z), i w overline(z) - i z overline(w), z overline(z) - w overline(w))$. Assuming that $tau_2$ is a smooth surjective submersion, then $tau$ is as well. A fiber of $pi$ is given by all the complex multiples of a nonzero complex vector. So let $(z,w) in CC^2$ and $alpha in CC$, and let's compute $tau(alpha z, alpha w)$. The second one is equal to $frac(1, abs(alpha)^2 (abs(z)^2+abs(w)^2))(alpha z overline(alpha w) + alpha w overline(alpha z), i alpha w overline(alpha z) - i alpha z overline(alpha w), alpha z overline(alpha z) - alpha w overline(alpha w))$, and since $overline(alpha x) = overline(alpha) dot overline(x)$ and $alpha overline(alpha) = abs(alpha)^2$, $tau$ is constant on the fibers of $pi$. Now, without loss of generality, take $(z_1,w_1), (z_2,w_2) in SS^3$ and assume that $tau_2 (z_1,w_1) = tau_2 (z_2,w_2)$. We wish to show that $pi$ is constant on these two points. 

 Before we do this, note that $(z overline(w) + w overline(z), i w overline(z) - i z overline(w), z overline(z) - w overline(w))$ can be rewritten as $(2 Re(z overline(w)), 2 Im(z overline(w) ), abs(z)^2-abs(w)^2)$. So we get the equations $Re(z_1 overline(w_1)) = Re(z_2 overline(w_2))$, $Im (z_1 overline(w_1)) = Im(z_2 overline(w_2))$, and $abs(z_1)^2 - abs(w_1)^2 = abs(z_2)^2 - abs(w_2)^2$ (though two equations determine the other, so this doesn't matter). Note that we would like for the structure of the fiber of $tau_2$ to be diffeomorphic to $SS^1$, since $SS^1 times RR tilde.equiv CC^times$ (the fiber structure for $pi$) and since $RR tilde.equiv (0,infinity)$ is the fiber structure of $tau_1$. Secondly, note that $Re(z_i overline(w_i)) = abs(w_i)^2 Re(z_i/w_i)$, and likewise for $Im$, for $i=1,2$. So $abs(w_1)^2 z_1/w_1 = abs(w_2)^2 z_2/w_2$. Let $f(z,w) = abs(w)^2 z/w$. Now, let's consider how, given $r e^(i theta)$ and $s e^(i phi)$ in standard form, convert to another pair of complex numbers that shares the same value on $f(z,w)$. The most obvious way to do this is to add the same number to both $theta$ and $phi$. This is also compatible with the other equations. The other variable under our control is the magnitude of the two numbers. In particular, if $r$ is multiplied by a real, positive factor $alpha$, then the solution for the other variable, $t s e^(i phi)$, satisfies $t^2 s^2 frac(alpha r e^(i theta), t s e^(i phi)) = s^2 frac(r e^(i theta), s e^(i phi))$. So $t s alpha = s$, and $t = alpha^(-1)$. Fortunately, when $alpha eq.not 1$, $abs(r)^2 - abs(s)^2 eq.not alpha^2 abs( r)^2 - alpha^(-2) abs(s)^2$, which can be seen by taking derivatives with respect to $alpha$. So indeed the fiber structure of $tau_2$ is $SS^1$ and $pi$ is constant on each fiber.

 Finally, we must show that $tau_2$ is a surjective smooth submersion. For surjectivity, as we have seen, it suffices to show that $2z overline(w)$ can take on all values in $CC^times$ and that $abs(z)^2 - abs(w)^2$ can take on either of its possible values. The second condition is easy: $(overline(w), overline(z))$ takes on the same value as $(z,w)$ in the first variable while swapping around the second. In addition, $CC^times$ is a group, and conjugation is a bijection, so left-multiplication is a bijection. So $tau_2$ is surjective. To show that $tau_2$ is smooth, observe that we can just check $tau_2$ as a map on the manifolds $RR^4$ and $RR^3$, for which $SS^3$ and $SS^2$ are respectively immersed submanifolds at least, by Theorems 5.27 and Theorems 5.29. On these larger manifolds, $tau_2$ is obviously a smooth map. To see that $tau_2$ is a submersion, we calculate its Jacobian matrix at $(x,y,z,w) in RR^4$. We compute $(x+i y)(z-i w) = x z + y w +i y z - i x w$ and $abs(x + i y)^2 - abs(z + i w)^2=x^2+y^2-z^2-w^2$. So $ J_(x,y,z,w)  = mat(2z, 2w, 2x, 2y; -2w, 2z, 2y, -2x; 2x, 2y, -2z, -2w). $

We just need to show that this is of full rank on $RR^4 \\ {0}$, since $SS&^3$  is an embedded submanifold of $RR^4 \\ {0}$ (by Example 5.9). A way to do this is to look at the graph minors. For example, the determinant of the first graph minor is $8(-y w^2 -x z w-x^2 y + x z w - y^3  -y z^2)$. If one sums the graph minor determinants, one finds that the matrix is of full rank as long as the point is non-zero.

Now, to see that $tau_2$ is a smooth submersion as a map from $SS^3$ to $SS^2$, observe that the tangent space of a point in $SS^3$ is three-dimensional, and likewise for $SS^2$. Since $d tau_2$ on $RR^4 \\ {0}$ has constant rank 3, on a point $p in SS^3$, a basis for $T_p (RR^4 \\ {0})$ that contains (exactly) three vectors in $T_p SS^3$ will be sent to a rank-3 set in $T_(tau_2 (p)) (RR^3 \\ {0})$. Three vectors will be mapped into $T_(tau_2 (p)) (SS^2)$ (there is no hope of $d tau_2$ having rank 3 if all vectors are sent here), and the dimension of their span can be at most 2. It cannot be less than 2, because the span of the vector not within $T_(tau_2 (p)) (SS^2)$ combined with this set would in that case have dimension at most 2, as a basis could be given by an element in $T_(tau_2 (p)) (SS^2)$ and the one not in that tangent space. and the basis vectors on the 3-sphere will be sent to a rank-2 set in $T_(tau_2 (p)) (SS^2)$.